sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Adversaries may employ various system checks to detect and avoid virtualization and analysis environments.
This may include changing behaviors based on the results of checks for the presence of artifacts indicative of a virtual machine environment (VME) or sandbox

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered unknown. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The script starts by opening a URL using the default web browser.
It then retrieves the computer's domain name.
If the domain is "WORKGROUP", nothing further happens.
Otherwise, it executes a series of commands to extract files from 7z archives using "66.exe". The first archive "admin3.7z" is extracted to "C:\Users\Public\Pictures\admin". Two additional archives, "admin2.7z", and "admin1.7z" located within the previously extracted folder, are subsequently extracted into the same directory.
Finally, the script executes "C:\Users\Public\Pictures\admin\start.exe".

The provided PowerShell code is classified as malicious due to its behavior. The script first sets a variable $url to "https://www.google.com/chrome/" and then executes the Start-Process cmdlet with this URL. This initial part seems benign, as it appears to open a web browser to the specified URL.

However, the script then retrieves the domain of the computer using Get-WmiObject Win32_ComputerSystem and checks if the domain is equal to "WORKGROUP". If the domain is not "WORKGROUP", the script proceeds to execute a series of commands using cmd /c to extract files from encrypted archives using a tool named "66.exe" located in a suspicious directory "VFS\ProgramFilesX64\66\". The extracted files are placed in the directory C:\Users\Public\Pictures\admin with specific passwords for decryption.

After extracting the files, the script sets a variable $path to "C:\Users\Public\Pictures\admin\start.exe" and launches this executable using Start-Process. This final step indicates an attempt to run an unknown executable obtained from the extracted archives, which could potentially be malicious.

In summary, the code exhibits behavior associated with downloading and executing potentially harmful files from remote locations, indicating malicious intent.
